# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-data
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-data/abacus] An abacus consists of a two-dimensional array of slidable beads (or similar objects).
[src:digital-data/abacus] In their earliest designs, the beads could be loose on a flat surface or sliding in grooves.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Later the beads were made to slide on rods and built into a frame, allowing faster manipulation.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Each rod typically represents one digit of a multi-digit number laid out using a positional numeral system such as base ten (though some cultures used different numerical bases).
[src:digital-data/abacus] Roman and East Asian abacuses use a system resembling bi-quinary coded decimal, with a top deck (containing one or two beads) representing fives and a bottom deck (containing four or five beads) representing ones.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Natural numbers are normally used, but some allow simple fractional components (e.g.
[src:digital-data/abacus] 1⁄2, 1⁄4, and 1⁄12 in Roman abacus), and a decimal point can be imagined for fixed-point arithmetic.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Any particular abacus design supports multiple methods to perform calculations, including addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and square and cube roots.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The beads are first arranged to represent a number, then are manipulated to perform a mathematical operation with another number, and their final position can be read as the result (or can be used as the starting number for subsequent operations).
[src:digital-data/abacus] In the ancient world, abacuses were a practical calculating tool.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It was widely used in Europe as late as the 17th century, but fell out of use with the rise of decimal notation and algorismic methods.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Although calculators and computers are commonly used today instead of abacuses, abacuses remain in everyday use in some countries.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The abacus has an advantage of not requiring a writing implement and paper (needed for algorism) or an electric power source.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Merchants, traders, and clerks in some parts of Eastern Europe, Russia, China, and Africa use abacuses.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The abacus remains in common use as a scoring system in non-electronic table games.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Others may use an abacus due to visual impairment that prevents the use of a calculator.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The abacus is still used to teach the fundamentals of mathematics to children in many countries such as Japan and China.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The word *abacus* dates to at least 1387 AD when a Middle English work borrowed the word from Latin that described a sandboard abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Latin word is derived from ancient Greek ἄβαξ (*abax*) which means something without a base, and colloquially, any piece of rectangular material.
[src:digital-data/abacus] While the table strewn with dust definition is popular, some argue evidence is insufficient for that conclusion.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Greek ἄβαξ probably borrowed from a Northwest Semitic language like Phoenician, evidenced by a cognate with the Hebrew word *ʾābāq* (אבק‎), or "dust" (in the post-Biblical sense "sand used as a writing surface").
[src:digital-data/abacus] Both *abacuses* and *abaci* are used as plurals.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The user of an abacus is called an *abacist*.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Sumerian abacus appeared between 2700 and 2300 BC.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It held a table of successive columns which delimited the successive orders of magnitude of their sexagesimal (base 60) number system.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Primitive forms of the abacus existed in Sumer, such as the non-fixed bead abacus, a line of strings fixed to a board, counting strings consisting of beads (similar to prayer beads and pace count beads), ropes and knots, and counting boards (similar to tally sticks).
[src:digital-data/abacus] The exact form and function of these devices are scattered around different sources, and their exact relation to the modern abacus is unknown but it is almost certain there is a relationship with masihatu, which functioned similar to an abacus utilizing multiple strings and sets of beads.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Some scholars point to a character in Babylonian cuneiform that may have been derived from a representation of the abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It is the belief of Old Babylonian scholars, such as Ettore Carruccio, that Old Babylonians "seem to have used the abacus for the operations of addition and subtraction; however, this primitive device proved difficult to use for more complex calculations".
[src:digital-data/abacus] Greek historian Herodotus mentioned the abacus in Ancient Egypt.
[src:digital-data/abacus] He wrote that the Egyptians manipulated the pebbles from right to left, opposite in direction to the Greek left-to-right method.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Archaeologists have found ancient disks of various sizes that are thought to have been used as counters.
[src:digital-data/abacus] However, there are no known illustrations of this device.
[src:digital-data/abacus] At around 600 BC, Persians first began to use the abacus during the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Under the Parthians, Sasanians, as well as later succeding empires, scholars concentrated on exchanging knowledge and inventions with the countries around them — India, China, and the Roman Empire — which is how the abacus may have been exported to other countries.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The earliest archaeological evidence for the use of the Greek abacus dates to the 5th century BC.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Demosthenes (384–322 BC) complained that the need to use pebbles for calculations was too difficult.
[src:digital-data/abacus] A play by Alexis from the 4th century BC mentions an abacus and pebbles for accounting, and both Diogenes and Polybius use the abacus as a metaphor for human behavior, stating "that men that sometimes stood for more and sometimes for less" like the pebbles on an abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Greek abacus was a table of wood or marble, pre-set with small counters in wood or metal for mathematical calculations.
[src:digital-data/abacus] This Greek abacus was used in Achaemenid Persia, the Etruscan civilization, Ancient Rome, and the Western Christian world until the French Revolution.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Salamis Tablet, found on the Greek island Salamis in 1846 AD, dates to 300 BC, making it the oldest counting board discovered so far.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It is a slab of white marble 149 cm (59 in) in length, 75 cm (30 in) wide, and 4.5 cm (2 in) thick, on which are 5 groups of markings.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In the tablet's center is a set of 5 parallel lines equally divided by a vertical line, capped with a semicircle at the intersection of the bottom-most horizontal line and the single vertical line.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Below these lines is a wide space with a horizontal crack dividing it.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Below this crack is another group of eleven parallel lines, again divided into two sections by a line perpendicular to them, but with the semicircle at the top of the intersection; the third, sixth and ninth of these lines are marked with a cross where they intersect with the vertical line.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Also from this time frame, the Darius Vase was unearthed in 1851.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It was covered with pictures, including a "treasurer" holding a wax tablet in one hand while manipulating counters on a table with the other.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The normal method of calculation in ancient Rome, as in Greece, was by moving counters on a smooth table.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Originally pebbles (Latin: *calculi*) were used.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Marked lines indicated units, fives, tens, etc. as in the Roman numeral system.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Writing in the 1st century BC, Horace refers to the wax abacus, a board covered with a thin layer of black wax on which columns and figures were inscribed using a stylus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] One example of archaeological evidence of the Roman abacus, shown nearby in reconstruction, dates to the 1st century AD.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It has eight long grooves containing up to five beads in each and eight shorter grooves having either one or no beads in each.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The groove marked I indicates units, X tens, and so on up to millions.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The beads in the shorter grooves denote fives (five units, five tens, etc.) resembling a bi-quinary coded decimal system related to the Roman numerals.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The short grooves on the right may have been used for marking Roman "ounces" (i.e. fractions).
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Roman system of 'counter casting' was used widely in medieval Europe, and persisted in limited use into the nineteenth century.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Wealthy abacists used decorative minted counters, called jetons.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Due to Pope Sylvester II's reintroduction of the abacus with modifications, it became widely used in Europe again during the 11th century.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It used beads on wires, unlike the traditional Roman counting boards, which meant the abacus could be used much faster and was more easily moved.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Russian abacus, the *schoty* (Russian: счёты, plural from Russian: счёт, counting), usually has a single slanted deck, with ten beads on each wire (except one wire with four beads for quarter-ruble fractions).
[src:digital-data/abacus] 4-bead wire was introduced for quarter-kopeks, which were minted until 1916.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Russian abacus is used vertically, with each wire running horizontally.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The wires are usually bowed upward in the center, to keep the beads pinned to either side.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It is cleared when all the beads are moved to the right.
[src:digital-data/abacus] During manipulation, beads are moved to the left.
[src:digital-data/abacus] For easy viewing, the middle 2 beads on each wire (the 5th and 6th bead) usually are of a different color from the other eight.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Likewise, the left bead of the thousands wire (and the million wire, if present) may have a different color.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Russian abacus was in use in shops and markets throughout the former Soviet Union, and its usage was taught in most schools until the 1990s.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Even the 1874 invention of mechanical calculator, Odhner arithmometer, had not replaced them in Russia.
[src:digital-data/abacus] According to Yakov Perelman, some businessmen attempting to import calculators into the Russian Empire were known to leave in despair after watching a skilled abacus operator.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Likewise, the mass production of Felix arithmometers since 1924 did not significantly reduce abacus use in the Soviet Union.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Russian abacus began to lose popularity only after the mass production of domestic microcalculators in 1974.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Russian abacus was brought to France around 1820 by mathematician Jean-Victor Poncelet, who had served in Napoleon's army and had been a prisoner of war in Russia.
[src:digital-data/abacus] To Poncelet's French contemporaries, it was something new.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Poncelet used it, not for any applied purpose, but as a teaching and demonstration aid.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Turks and the Armenian people used abacuses similar to the Russian schoty.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It was named a *coulba* by the Turks and a *choreb* by the Armenians.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The earliest known written documentation of the Chinese abacus dates to the 2nd century BC.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Chinese abacus, also known as the *suanpan* (算盤/算盘, lit.
[src:digital-data/abacus] "calculating tray"), comes in various lengths and widths, depending on the operator.
[src:digital-data/abacus] There are two beads on each rod in the upper deck and five beads each in the bottom one, to represent numbers in a bi-quinary coded decimal-like system.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The beads are usually rounded and made of hardwood.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The beads are counted by moving them up or down towards the beam; beads moved toward the beam are counted, while those moved away from it are not.
[src:digital-data/abacus] One of the top beads is 5, while one of the bottom beads is 1.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Each rod has a number under it, showing the place value.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The *suanpan* can be reset to the starting position instantly by a quick movement along the horizontal axis to spin all the beads away from the horizontal beam at the center.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The prototype of the Chinese abacus appeared during the Han dynasty, and the beads are oval.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Song dynasty and earlier used the 1:4 type or four-beads abacus similar to the modern abacus including the shape of the beads commonly known as Japanese-style abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In the early Ming dynasty, the abacus began to appear in a 1:5 ratio.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The upper deck had one bead and the bottom had five beads.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In the late Ming dynasty, the abacus styles appeared in a 2:5 ratio.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The upper deck had two beads, and the bottom had five.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Various calculation techniques were devised for *suanpan* enabling efficient calculations.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Some schools teach students how to use it.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In the long scroll *Along the River During the Qingming Festival* painted by Zhang Zeduan during the Song dynasty (960–1297), a *suanpan* is clearly visible beside an account book and doctor's prescriptions on the counter of an apothecary's (Feibao).
[src:digital-data/abacus] The similarity of the Roman abacus to the Chinese one suggests that one could have inspired the other, given evidence of a trade relationship between the Roman Empire and China.
[src:digital-data/abacus] However, no direct connection has been demonstrated, and the similarity of the abacuses may be coincidental, both ultimately arising from counting with five fingers per hand.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Where the Roman model (like most modern Korean and Japanese) has 4 plus 1 bead per decimal place, the standard *suanpan* has 5 plus 2.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Incidentally, this ancient Chinese calculation system 市用制 (*Shì yòng zhì*) allows use with a hexadecimal numeral system (or any base up to 18) which is used for traditional Chinese measures of weight [(*jīn* (斤) and *liǎng* (兩)].
[src:digital-data/abacus] Instead of running on wires as in the Chinese, Korean, and Japanese models, the Roman model used grooves, presumably making arithmetic calculations much slower.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Another possible source of the *suanpan* is Chinese counting rods, which operated with a decimal system but lacked the concept of zero as a placeholder.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The zero was probably introduced to the Chinese in the Tang dynasty (618–907) when travel in the Indian Ocean and the Middle East would have provided direct contact with India, allowing them to acquire the concept of zero and the decimal point from Indian merchants and mathematicians.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In Japan, the abacus is called *soroban* (算盤, そろばん, lit.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It was imported from China in the 14th century.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It was probably in use by the working class a century or more before the ruling class adopted it, as rigid class structures slowed the spread of such innovations.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The 1:4 abacus, which removes the seldom-used second and fifth bead, became popular in the 1940s.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Today's Japanese abacus is a 1:4 type, four-bead abacus, introduced from China in the Muromachi era.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It adopts the form of the upper deck one bead and the bottom four beads.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The top bead on the upper deck was equal to five and the bottom one is similar to the Chinese or Korean abacus, and the decimal number can be expressed, so the abacus is designed as a 1:4 device.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The beads are always in the shape of a diamond.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The quotient division is generally used instead of the division method; at the same time, in order to make the multiplication and division digits consistently use the division multiplication.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Later, Japan had a 3:5 abacus called 天三算盤, which is now in the Ize Rongji collection of Shansi Village in Yamagata City.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The four-bead abacus spread, and became common around the world.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Improvements to the Japanese abacus arose in various places.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In China, an abacus with an aluminium frame and plastic beads has been used.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The file is next to the four beads, and pressing the "clearing" button puts the upper bead in the upper position, and the lower bead in the lower position.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The abacus is still manufactured in Japan, despite the proliferation, practicality, and affordability of pocket electronic calculators.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The use of the soroban is still taught in Japanese primary schools as part of mathematics, primarily as an aid to faster mental calculation.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Using visual imagery, one can complete a calculation as quickly as with a physical instrument.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Chinese abacus migrated from China to Korea around 1400 AD.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Koreans call the abacus *jupan* (주판) or *supan* (수판), and the act of using a jupan is *jusan* (주산).
[src:digital-data/abacus] The four-beads abacus (1:4) was introduced during the Goryeo Dynasty.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The 5:1 abacus was introduced to Korea from China during the Ming Dynasty.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It is unclear exactly what this arrangement may have been.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Around the 5th century, Indian clerks were already finding new ways of recording the contents of the abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Hindu texts used the term *śūnya* (zero) to indicate the empty column on the abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Since 2020, the organization Indian Abacus has run a national abacus competition in India.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Some sources mention the use of an abacus called a *nepohualtzintzin* in ancient Aztec culture.
[src:digital-data/abacus] This Mesoamerican abacus used a 5-digit base-20 system.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The word Nepōhualtzintzin Nahuatl pronunciation: [nepoːwaɬˈt͡sint͡sin] comes from Nahuatl, formed by the roots; *Ne* – personal -; *pōhual* or *pōhualli* Nahuatl pronunciation: [ˈpoːwalːi] – the account -; and *tzintzin* Nahuatl pronunciation: [ˈt͡sint͡sin] – small similar elements.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Its complete meaning was taken as: counting with small similar elements.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Its use was taught in the Calmecac to the *temalpouhqueh* Nahuatl pronunciation: [temaɬˈpoʍkeʔ], who were students dedicated to taking the accounts of skies, from childhood.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The Nepōhualtzintzin was divided into two main parts separated by a bar or intermediate cord.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Beads in the first row have unitary values (1, 2, 3, and 4), and on the right side, three beads had values of 5, 10, and 15, respectively.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In order to know the value of the respective beads of the upper rows, it is enough to multiply by 20 (by each row), the value of the corresponding count in the first row.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The device featured 13 rows with 7 beads, 91 in total.
[src:digital-data/abacus] This was a basic number for this culture.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It had a close relation to natural phenomena, the underworld, and the cycles of the heavens.
[src:digital-data/abacus] When translated into modern computer arithmetic, the Nepōhualtzintzin amounted to the rank from 10 to 18 in floating point, which precisely calculated large and small amounts, although round off was not allowed.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The rediscovery of the Nepōhualtzintzin was due to the Mexican engineer David Esparza Hidalgo, who in his travels throughout Mexico found diverse engravings and paintings of this instrument and reconstructed several of them in gold, jade, encrustations of shell, etc.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Very old Nepōhualtzintzin are attributed to the Olmec culture, and some bracelets of Mayan origin, as well as a diversity of forms and materials in other cultures.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Sanchez wrote in *Arithmetic in Maya* that another base 5, base 4 abacus had been found in the Yucatán Peninsula that also computed calendar data.
[src:digital-data/abacus] This was a finger abacus, on one hand, 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4 were used; and on the other hand 0, 1, 2, and 3 were used.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Note the use of zero at the beginning and end of the two cycles.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The quipu of the Incas was a system of colored knotted cords used to record numerical data, like advanced tally sticks – but not used to perform calculations.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Calculations were carried out using a yupana (Quechua for "counting tool"; see figure) which was still in use after the conquest of Peru.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The working principle of a yupana is unknown, but in 2001 Italian mathematician De Pasquale proposed an explanation.
[src:digital-data/abacus] By comparing the form of several yupanas, researchers found that calculations were based using the Fibonacci sequence 1, 1, 2, 3, 5 and powers of 10, 20, and 40 as place values for the different fields in the instrument.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Using the Fibonacci sequence would keep the number of grains within any one field at a minimum.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Around the world, abacuses have been used in pre-schools and elementary schools as an aid in teaching the numeral system and arithmetic.
[src:digital-data/abacus] In Western countries, a bead frame similar to the Russian abacus but with straight wires and a vertical frame is common (see image).
[src:digital-data/abacus] Unlike other abaci, each bead represents one unit irrespective of which wire it is on.
[src:digital-data/abacus] E.g., 42 can be represented by shifting all 10 beads on four wires and two beads on a fifth wire.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Thus, in the bead frame shown, numbers up to 100 may be represented.
[src:digital-data/abacus] 6 times 7, may be represented by shifting 7 beads on 6 wires, subsequently rearranged to show 42 as described before.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The red-and-white abacus is used in contemporary primary schools for a wide range of number-related lessons.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The twenty bead version, referred to by its Dutch name *rekenrek* ("calculating frame"), is often used, either on a string of beads or on a rigid framework.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The binary abacus is used to explain how computers manipulate numbers.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The abacus shows how numbers, letters, and signs can be stored in a binary system on a computer, or via ASCII.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The device consists of beads on parallel wires arranged in three rows; each bead represents a switch which can be either "on" or "off".
[src:digital-data/abacus] Atomic-scale abacuses can be constructed using nanotechnology.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The first such nano-abacus was developed by IBM in 1997.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Learning how to calculate with the abacus may improve capacity for mental calculation.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Abacus-based mental calculation (AMC), which was derived from the abacus, is the act of performing calculations, including addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division, in the mind by manipulating an imagined abacus.
[src:digital-data/abacus] It is a high-level cognitive skill that runs calculations with an effective algorithm.
[src:digital-data/abacus] People doing long-term AMC training show higher numerical memory capacity and experience more effectively connected neural pathways.
[src:digital-data/abacus] They are able to retrieve memory to deal with complex processes.
[src:digital-data/abacus] AMC involves both visuospatial and visuomotor processing that generate the visual abacus and move the imaginary beads.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Since it only requires that the final position of beads be remembered, it takes less memory and less computation time.
[src:digital-data/abacus] An adapted abacus, invented by Tim Cranmer, and called a Cranmer abacus is commonly used by visually impaired users.
[src:digital-data/abacus] A piece of soft fabric or rubber is placed behind the beads, keeping them in place while the users manipulate them.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The device is then used to perform the mathematical functions of multiplication, division, addition, subtraction, square root, and cube root.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Although blind students have benefited from talking calculators, the abacus is often taught to these students in early grades.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Blind students can also complete mathematical assignments using a braille-writer and Nemeth code (a type of braille code for mathematics) but large multiplication and long division problems are tedious.
[src:digital-data/abacus] The abacus gives these students a tool to compute mathematical problems that equals the speed and mathematical knowledge required by their sighted peers using pencil and paper.
[src:digital-data/abacus] Many blind people find this number machine a useful tool throughout life.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The **Advanced Encryption Standard** (**AES**), also known by its original name **Rijndael** (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈrɛindaːl], *RAIN-dahl*), is a specification for the encryption of electronic data established by the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) in 2001.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is a variant of the Rijndael block cipher developed by two Belgian cryptographers, Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen, who submitted a proposal to NIST during the AES selection process.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Rijndael is a family of ciphers with different key and block sizes.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] For AES, NIST selected three members of the Rijndael family, each with a block size of 128 bits, but three different key lengths: 128, 192 and 256 bits.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has been adopted by the US government.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] It supersedes the Data Encryption Standard (DES), which was published in 1977.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The algorithm described by AES is a symmetric-key algorithm, meaning the same key is used for both encrypting and decrypting the data.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In the United States, AES was announced by the NIST as the US FIPS PUB 197 (FIPS 197) standard on November 26, 2001.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This announcement followed a five-year standardization process in which fifteen competing designs were presented and evaluated, before the Rijndael cipher was selected as the most suitable.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is included in the ISO/IEC 18033-3 standard.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES became effective as a US federal government standard on May 26, 2002, after approval by US secretary of commerce Donald Evans.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is available in many different encryption packages, and is the first (and only) publicly accessible cipher approved by the US National Security Agency (NSA) for top secret information when used in an NSA approved cryptographic module.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is based on a design principle known as a substitution–permutation network, and is efficient in both software and hardware.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Unlike its predecessor DES, AES does not use a Feistel network.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is a variant of Rijndael, with a fixed block size of 128 bits, and a key size of 128, 192, or 256 bits.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] By contrast, Rijndael *per se* is specified with block and key sizes that may be any multiple of 32 bits, with a minimum of 128 and a maximum of 256 bits.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Most AES calculations are done in a particular finite field.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The key size used for an AES cipher specifies the number of transformation rounds that convert the input, called the plaintext, into the final output, called the ciphertext.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Each round consists of several processing steps, including one that depends on the encryption key itself.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] A set of reverse rounds are applied to transform ciphertext back into the original plaintext using the same encryption key.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] ShiftRows – a transposition step where the last three rows of the state are shifted cyclically a certain number of steps.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] MixColumns – a linear mixing operation which operates on the columns of the state, combining the four bytes in each column.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In the SubBytes step, each byte *ai,j* in the *state* array is replaced with a SubByte *S*(*ai,j*) using an 8-bit substitution box.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Before round 0, the *state* array is simply the plaintext/input.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This operation provides the non-linearity in the cipher.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The S-box used is derived from the multiplicative inverse over GF(28), known to have good non-linearity properties.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] To avoid attacks based on simple algebraic properties, the S-box is constructed by combining the inverse function with an invertible affine transformation.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The S-box is also chosen to avoid any fixed points (and so is a derangement), i.e., *S*(*ai,j*) ≠ *ai,j*, and also any opposite fixed points, i.e., *S*(*ai,j*) ⊕ *ai,j* ≠ FF16.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] While performing the decryption, the InvSubBytes step (the inverse of SubBytes) is used, which requires first taking the inverse of the affine transformation and then finding the multiplicative inverse.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The ShiftRows step operates on the rows of the state; it cyclically shifts the bytes in each row by a certain offset.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] For AES, the first row is left unchanged.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Each byte of the second row is shifted one to the left.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Similarly, the third and fourth rows are shifted by offsets of two and three respectively.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In this way, each column of the output state of the ShiftRows step is composed of bytes from each column of the input state.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The importance of this step is to avoid the columns being encrypted independently, in which case AES would degenerate into four independent block ciphers.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In the MixColumns step, the four bytes of each column of the state are combined using an invertible linear transformation.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The MixColumns function takes four bytes as input and outputs four bytes, where each input byte affects all four output bytes.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Together with ShiftRows, MixColumns provides diffusion in the cipher.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Matrix multiplication is composed of multiplication and addition of the entries.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Entries are bytes treated as coefficients of polynomial of order *x*7.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Multiplication is modulo irreducible polynomial *x*8 + *x*4 + *x*3 + *x* + 1.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] If processed bit by bit, then, after shifting, a conditional XOR with 1B16 should be performed if the shifted value is larger than FF16 (overflow must be corrected by subtraction of generating polynomial).
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] These are special cases of the usual multiplication in GF(28).
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The coefficients are displayed in their hexadecimal equivalent of the binary representation of bit polynomials from GF(28)[*x*].
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The MixColumns step can also be viewed as a multiplication by the shown particular MDS matrix in the finite field GF(28).
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This process is described further in the article Rijndael MixColumns.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In the AddRoundKey step, the subkey is combined with the state.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] For each round, a subkey is derived from the main key using Rijndael's key schedule; each subkey is the same size as the state.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The subkey is added by combining of the state with the corresponding byte of the subkey using bitwise XOR.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] On systems with 32-bit or larger words, it is possible to speed up execution of this cipher by combining the SubBytes and ShiftRows steps with the MixColumns step by transforming them into a sequence of table lookups.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This requires four 256-entry 32-bit tables (together occupying 4096 bytes).
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] A round can then be performed with 16 table lookup operations and 12 32-bit exclusive-or operations, followed by four 32-bit exclusive-or operations in the AddRoundKey step.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Alternatively, the table lookup operation can be performed with a single 256-entry 32-bit table (occupying 1024 bytes) followed by circular rotation operations.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Using a byte-oriented approach, it is possible to combine the SubBytes, ShiftRows, and MixColumns steps into a single round operation.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The National Security Agency (NSA) reviewed all the AES finalists, including Rijndael, and stated that all of them were secure enough for US Government non-classified data.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has 10 rounds for 128-bit keys, 12 rounds for 192-bit keys, and 14 rounds for 256-bit keys.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] More recent guidance from the NSA, however, only allows classified information to be encrypted with 256-bit key lengths.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] 128-bit and 192-bits is no longer sufficient for the encryption of classified information.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] For cryptographers, a cryptographic "break" is anything faster than a brute-force attack – i.e., performing one trial decryption for each possible key in sequence .
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] A break can thus include results that are infeasible with current technology.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Despite being impractical, theoretical breaks can sometimes provide insight into vulnerability patterns.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The largest successful publicly known brute-force attack against a widely implemented block-cipher encryption algorithm was against a 64-bit RC5 key by distributed.net in 2006.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The key space increases by a factor of 2 for each additional bit of key length, and if every possible value of the key is equiprobable; this translates into a doubling of the average brute-force key search time with every additional bit of key length.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This implies that the effort of a brute-force search increases exponentially with key length.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Key length in itself does not imply security against attacks, since there are ciphers with very long keys that have been found to be vulnerable.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has a fairly simple algebraic framework.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In 2002, a theoretical attack, named the "XSL attack", was announced by Nicolas Courtois and Josef Pieprzyk, purporting to show a weakness in the AES algorithm, partially due to the low complexity of its nonlinear components.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Since then, other papers have shown that the attack, as originally presented, is unworkable; see XSL attack on block ciphers.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] By 2006, the best known attacks were on 7 rounds for 128-bit keys, 8 rounds for 192-bit keys, and 9 rounds for 256-bit keys.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Until May 2009, the only successful published attacks against the full AES were side-channel attacks on some specific implementations.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In 2009, a new related-key attack was discovered that exploits the simplicity of AES's key schedule and has a complexity of 2119.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In December 2009 it was improved to 299.5.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This is a follow-up to an attack discovered earlier in 2009 by Alex Biryukov, Dmitry Khovratovich, and Ivica Nikolić, with a complexity of 296 for one out of every 235 keys.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] However, related-key attacks are not of concern in any properly designed cryptographic protocol, as a properly designed protocol (i.e., implementational software) will take care not to allow related keys, essentially by constraining an attacker's means of selecting keys for relatedness.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Another attack was blogged by Bruce Schneier on July 30, 2009, and released as a preprint on August 3, 2009.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] 256-bit AES uses 14 rounds, so these attacks are not effective against full AES.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The practicality of these attacks with stronger related keys has been criticized, for instance, by the paper on chosen-key-relations-in-the-middle attacks on AES-128 authored by Vincent Rijmen in 2010.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In November 2009, the first known-key distinguishing attack against a reduced 8-round version of AES-128 was released as a preprint.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This known-key distinguishing attack is an improvement of the rebound, or the start-from-the-middle attack, against AES-like permutations, which view two consecutive rounds of permutation as the application of a so-called Super-S-box.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] It works on the 8-round version of AES-128, with a time complexity of 248, and a memory complexity of 232.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] 128-bit AES uses 10 rounds, so this attack is not effective against full AES-128.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The first key-recovery attacks on full AES were by Andrey Bogdanov, Dmitry Khovratovich, and Christian Rechberger, and were published in 2011.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The attack is a biclique attack and is faster than brute force by a factor of about four.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] It requires 2126.2 operations to recover an AES-128 key.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This result has been further improved to 2126.0 for AES-128, 2189.9 for AES-192, and 2254.3 for AES-256 by Biaoshuai Tao and Hongjun Wu in a 2015 paper, which are the current best results in key recovery attack against AES.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This is a very small gain, as a 126-bit key (instead of 128 bits) would still take billions of years to brute force on current and foreseeable hardware.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Also, the authors calculate the best attack using their technique on AES with a 128-bit key requires storing 288 bits of data.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] That works out to about 38 trillion terabytes of data, which was more than all the data stored on all the computers on the planet in 2016.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] A paper in 2015 later improved the space complexity to 256 bits, which is 9007 terabytes (while still keeping a time complexity of approximately 2126).
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] According to the Snowden documents, the NSA is doing research on whether a cryptographic attack based on tau statistic may help to break AES.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] At present, there is no known practical attack that would allow someone without knowledge of the key to read data encrypted by AES when correctly implemented.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Side-channel attacks do not attack the cipher as a black box, and thus are not related to cipher security as defined in the classical context, but are important in practice.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] They attack implementations of the cipher on hardware or software systems that inadvertently leak data.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] There are several such known attacks on various implementations of AES.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Bernstein announced a cache-timing attack that he used to break a custom server that used OpenSSL's AES encryption.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The attack required over 200 million chosen plaintexts.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The custom server was designed to give out as much timing information as possible (the server reports back the number of machine cycles taken by the encryption operation).
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In October 2005, Dag Arne Osvik, Adi Shamir and Eran Tromer presented a paper demonstrating several cache-timing attacks against the implementations in AES found in OpenSSL and Linux's `dm-crypt` partition encryption function.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] One attack was able to obtain an entire AES key after only 800 operations triggering encryptions, in a total of 65 milliseconds.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This attack requires the attacker to be able to run programs on the same system or platform that is performing AES.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In December 2009 an attack on some hardware implementations was published that used differential fault analysis and allows recovery of a key with a complexity of 232.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] In November 2010, Endre Bangerter, David Gullasch and Stephan Krenn published a paper which described a practical approach to a "near real time" recovery of secret keys from AES-128 without the need for either cipher text or plaintext.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The approach also works on AES-128 implementations that use compression tables, such as OpenSSL.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Like some earlier attacks, this one requires the ability to run unprivileged code on the system performing the AES encryption, which may be achieved by malware infection far more easily than commandeering the root account.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The proposed attack requires standard user privilege and key-retrieval algorithms run under a minute.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Many modern CPUs have built-in hardware instructions for AES, which protect against timing-related side-channel attacks.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-256 is considered to be quantum resistant, as it has similar quantum resistance to AES-128's resistance against traditional, non-quantum, attacks at 128 bits of security.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-192 and AES-128 are not considered quantum resistant due to their smaller key sizes.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-192 has a strength of 96 bits against quantum attacks and AES-128 has 64 bits of strength against quantum attacks, making them both insecure.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) is operated jointly by the United States Government's National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Computer Security Division and the Communications Security Establishment (CSE) of the Government of Canada.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The use of cryptographic modules validated to NIST FIPS 140-2 is required by the United States Government for encryption of all data that has a classification of Sensitive but Unclassified (SBU) or above.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The Government of Canada also recommends the use of FIPS 140 validated cryptographic modules in unclassified applications of its departments.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Although NIST publication 197 ("FIPS 197") is the unique document that covers the AES algorithm, vendors typically approach the CMVP under FIPS 140 and ask to have several algorithms (such as Triple DES or SHA1) validated at the same time.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Therefore, it is rare to find cryptographic modules that are uniquely FIPS 197 validated and NIST itself does not generally take the time to list FIPS 197 validated modules separately on its public web site.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Instead, FIPS 197 validation is typically just listed as an "FIPS approved: AES" notation (with a specific FIPS 197 certificate number) in the current list of FIPS 140 validated cryptographic modules.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP) allows for independent validation of the correct implementation of the AES algorithm.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Successful validation results in being listed on the NIST validations page.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This testing is a pre-requisite for the FIPS 140-2 module validation.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] However, successful CAVP validation in no way implies that the cryptographic module implementing the algorithm is secure.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] A cryptographic module lacking FIPS 140-2 validation or specific approval by the NSA is not deemed secure by the US Government and cannot be used to protect government data.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] FIPS 140-2 validation is challenging to achieve both technically and fiscally.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] There is a standardized battery of tests as well as an element of source code review that must be passed over a period of a few weeks.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] The cost to perform these tests through an approved laboratory can be significant (e.g., well over US$30,000) and does not include the time it takes to write, test, document and prepare a module for validation.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] After validation, modules must be re-submitted and re-evaluated if they are changed in any way.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] This can vary from simple paperwork updates if the security functionality did not change to a more substantial set of re-testing if the security functionality was impacted by the change.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] Test vectors are a set of known ciphers for a given input and key.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] NIST distributes the reference of AES test vectors as AES Known Answer Test (KAT) Vectors.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] High speed and low RAM requirements were some of the criteria of the AES selection process.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] As the chosen algorithm, AES performed well on a wide variety of hardware, from 8-bit smart cards to high-performance computers.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] On a Pentium Pro, AES encryption requires 18 clock cycles per byte (cpb), equivalent to a throughput of about 11 MiB/s for a 200 MHz processor.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] On Intel Core and AMD Ryzen CPUs supporting AES-NI instruction set extensions, throughput can be multiple GiB/s.
[src:digital-data/advanced-encryption-standard] On an Intel Westmere CPU, AES encryption using AES-NI takes about 1.3 cpb for AES-128, and 1.8 cpb for AES-256.
[src:digital-data/alation] Alation Data Catalog is a data catalog that serves enterprises in organizing and consolidating their data.
[src:digital-data/alation] Alation launched its data catalog as their first product in 2015 to give data consumers an easy way to search for enterprise data with natural language.
[src:digital-data/alation] Alation was founded in 2012 by Satyen Sangani, Aaron Kalb, Feng Nui, and Venky Ganti.
[src:digital-data/alation] Alation co-founders Satyen Sangani and Aaron Kalb arrived at the solution from two different perspectives.
[src:digital-data/alation] Sangani had a background in economics and had worked as an executive at Oracle.
[src:digital-data/alation] He knew data users in large companies struggled to find and trust data; he theorized that machine learning could be used to help them.
[src:digital-data/alation] Kalb had experience in symbolic systems and had worked on Siri at Apple.
[src:digital-data/alation] He thought crowdsourcing could be used to solve the challenge.
[src:digital-data/alation] In 2012, the team combined those two ideas to create Alation.
[src:digital-data/alation] Its first solution, a data querying system powered by natural language processing, helped define the modern data catalog.
[src:digital-data/alation] The tool was designed to catalog data in an organization and make that data more accessible to more people.
[src:digital-data/alation] This concept is generally termed data democratization.
[src:digital-data/alation] As the company improved the solution, it eased the building of complex queries with collaboration features, enabled data catalog efforts, and integrated with different data and related technology products, such as Snowflake, Tableau, Databricks, and others.
[src:digital-data/alation] As of early 2021, the company had more than 250 customers, including AbbVie, American Family Insurance, Autozone, Cisco, Exelon, Finnair, Munich Re, New Balance, Pfizer, Scandinavian Airlines, and U.S.
[src:digital-data/alation] By October 2021, the company had increased that number to around 300 customers, adding GE Aviation, NASDAQ, and Regeneron, among others.
[src:digital-data/alation] In October 2021, Alation acquired Lyngo Analytics, a data insights company which develops software to help users find insights by asking questions in simple business terms.
[src:digital-data/alation] The acquisition is intended to deepen Alation’s ability to convert natural language questions from non-technical users into SQL queries.
[src:digital-data/alation] In January 2022, Alation launched the “Data Radicals” podcast hosted by the company’s CEO and co-founder, Satyen Sangani.
[src:digital-data/alation] The show is designed to help business, data, and technology enthusiasts use data in powerful ways.
[src:digital-data/alation] Guests have included Stan McChrystal, retired U.S.
[src:digital-data/alation] In September 2022, Alation announced that it had achieved $100 million of annual recurring revenue (ARR).
[src:digital-data/alation] On May 20, 2025, Alation announced that it had acquired Numbers Station AI, a pioneer in building AI agents for data workflows.
[src:digital-data/alation] This acquisition is intended to accelerate the ability of data and engineering teams to quickly build and deploy a new class of AI-native analytics applications featuring agentic workflows that operate with enterprise-grade governance and context.
[src:digital-data/alation] In early March 2015, the company announced it had raised $9 million in a Series A round led by Costanoa Ventures and Data Collective.
[src:digital-data/alation] Later that month, it emerged from “stealth mode” to launch its data catalog product.
[src:digital-data/alation] This latest investment round valued the company at $1.2 billion, making it an industry unicorn.
[src:digital-data/alation] In November 2022, Alation announced it has raised $123 million in a Series E financing led by Thoma Bravo, Sanabil Investments, and Costanoa Ventures, with participation from new investor, Databricks Ventures.
[src:digital-data/alation] Existing and other investors that also participated include Dell Technologies Capital, Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE), Icon Ventures, Queensland Investment Corporation, Riverwood Capital, Salesforce Ventures, Sapphire Ventures, and Union Grove.
[src:digital-data/alation] Alation has raised a total of $340 million and, as of its Series E funding, has a valuation of more than $1.7 billion.
[src:digital-data/alation] Alation is headquartered in Redwood City, CA.
[src:digital-data/alation] The company also has offices in London, U.K. and Chennai, India, and a presence in over 25 countries.
[src:digital-data/alation] As of November 2022, the company had over 700 global employees, an increase of 75% in less than 12 months.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In mathematics and computer science, an **algorithm** (/ˈælɡərɪðəm/ ⓘ) is a finite sequence of mathematically rigorous instructions, typically used to solve a class of specific problems or to perform a computation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms are used as specifications for performing calculations and data processing.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] More advanced algorithms can use conditionals to divert the code execution through various routes (referred to as automated decision-making) and deduce valid inferences (referred to as automated reasoning).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In contrast, a heuristic is an approach to solving problems without well-defined correct or optimal results.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] For example, although social media recommender systems are commonly called "algorithms", they actually rely on heuristics as there is no truly "correct" recommendation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] As an effective method, an algorithm can be expressed within a finite amount of space and time and in a well-defined formal language for calculating a function.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Starting from an initial state and input, a computation occurs at each step, eventually producing output and terminating.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The transition between states can be non-deterministic; randomized algorithms incorporate random input.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Around 825 AD, Persian scientist and polymath Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī wrote *kitāb al-ḥisāb al-hindī* ("Book of Indian computation") and *kitab al-jam' wa'l-tafriq al-ḥisāb al-hindī* ("Addition and subtraction in Indian arithmetic").
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In the early 12th century, Latin translations of these texts involving the Hindu–Arabic numeral system and arithmetic appeared, for example *Liber Alghoarismi de practica arismetrice*, attributed to John of Seville, and *Liber Algoritmi de numero Indorum*, attributed to Adelard of Bath.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Here, *alghoarismi* or *algoritmi* is the Latinization of Al-Khwarizmi's name; the text starts with the phrase *Dixit Algoritmi*, or "Thus spoke Al-Khwarizmi".
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The word *algorism* in English came to mean the use of place-value notation in calculations; it occurs in the *Ancrene Wisse* from circa 1225.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] By the time Geoffrey Chaucer wrote *The Canterbury Tales* in the late 14th century, he used a variant of the same word in describing *augrym stones*, stones used for place-value calculation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In the 15th century, under the influence of the Greek word ἀριθμός (*arithmos*, "number"; *cf.* "arithmetic"), the Latin word was altered to *algorithmus*.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] By 1596, this form of the word was used in English, as *algorithm*, by Thomas Hood.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] One informal definition is "a set of rules that precisely defines a sequence of operations", which would include all computer programs, and any bureaucratic procedure or cook-book recipe.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In general, a program is an algorithm only if it stops eventually.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Step-by-step procedures for solving mathematical problems have been recorded since antiquity.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] This includes in Babylonian mathematics (around 2500 BC), Egyptian mathematics (around 1550 BC), Indian mathematics (around 800 BC and later), the Ifa Oracle (around 500 BC), Greek mathematics (around 240 BC), Chinese mathematics (around 200 BC and later), and Arabic mathematics (around 800 AD).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The earliest evidence of algorithms is found in ancient Mesopotamian mathematics.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] A Sumerian clay tablet found in Shuruppak near Baghdad and dated to c.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] 2500 BC describes the earliest division algorithm.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] 1600 BC, Babylonian clay tablets described algorithms for computing formulas.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms were also used in Babylonian astronomy.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Babylonian clay tablets describe and employ algorithmic procedures to compute the time and place of significant astronomical events.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms for arithmetic are also found in ancient Egyptian mathematics, dating back to the Rhind Mathematical Papyrus c.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms were later used in ancient Hellenistic mathematics.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Two examples are the Sieve of Eratosthenes, which was described in the *Introduction to Arithmetic* by Nicomachus, and the Euclidean algorithm, which was first described in *Euclid's Elements* (c.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] 300 BC).Examples of ancient Indian mathematics included the Shulba Sutras, the Kerala School, and the Brāhmasphuṭasiddhānta.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In the 9th century, Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī revolutionized the field by establishing the algorithm as a systematic, finite sequence of logical steps to solve mathematical problems.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In his influential work, The Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion and Balancing, he moved beyond specific numerical solutions to introduce general procedures for algebraic reduction and balancing.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] This transformed mathematics into a 'mechanical' process of well-defined rules—a fundamental shift that laid the groundwork for modern algorithmic theory.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The Latin translation of his arithmetic treatise, titled Algoritmi de numero Indorum, led to the term algorithm being derived from the Latinization of his name, Algoritmi, specifically to describe this new rule-based approach to mathematics.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The first cryptographic algorithm for deciphering encrypted code was developed by Al-Kindi, a 9th-century Arab mathematician, in *A Manuscript On Deciphering Cryptographic Messages*.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] He gave the first description of cryptanalysis by frequency analysis, the earliest codebreaking algorithm.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Weight-driven clocks were a key European invention in Middle Ages, specifically the verge escapement mechanism producing the tick of mechanical clocks.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Accurate automatic machines led to mechanical automata in the 13th century and computational machines—the difference and analytical engines of Charles Babbage and Ada Lovelace in the mid-19th century.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Lovelace designed the first algorithm intended for a computer, Babbage's analytical engine, the first real Turing-complete computer, more than the mechanical calculators of the time.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Although the full implementation of Babbage's second device was only built decades after her lifetime, Lovelace has been called "history's first programmer".
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The Jacquard loom, a precursor to punch cards, and telephone switching machines led to the development of the first computers.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] By the mid-19th century, the telegraph, was in use throughout the world.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] By the late 19th century, ticker tape (c.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] 1910) with its punched-paper use of Baudot code on tape.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Telephone-switching networks of electromechanical relays were invented in 1835.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] These led to the invention of the digital adding device by George Stibitz in 1937.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] While working in Bell Laboratories, he observed the "burdensome" use of mechanical calculators with gears, prompting him to create an experimental digital adder at home.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In 1928, a partial formalization of the modern concept of algorithms began with attempts to solve David Hilbert's *Entscheidungsproblem*(decision problem).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Later formalizations were framed as attempts to define "effective calculability" or "effective method".
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Those formalizations included the Gödel–Herbrand–Kleene recursive functions of 1930, 1934 and 1935, Alonzo Church's lambda calculus of 1936, Emil Post's Formulation 1 of 1936, and Alan Turing's Turing machines of 1936–37 and 1939.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] For decades, it was assumed that algorithm evolution progresses from heuristics to formal algorithms.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] A Symbolic integration provides a classic illustration.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In 1961, James Slagle’s program SAINT used heuristics to solve 52 of 54 freshman calculus exercises from an MIT textbook (≈96%).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In 1967, Larry Moses’s SIN refined the heuristics and achieved 100% success, though it remained heuristic.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Finally, in 1969, Robert Risch introduced the Risch Algorithm with formal guarantees.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] This trajectory defined the traditional path: heuristics evolving until a definitive, guaranteed algorithm emerged.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] However, the rise of transformer-based AI has inverted this sequence — classical algorithms are now being displaced by heuristics once again.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms have evolved and improved in many ways as time goes on.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Common uses of algorithms today include social media apps like Instagram and YouTube.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms are used as a way to analyze what people like and push more of those things to the people who interact with them.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Quantum computing uses quantum algorithm procedures to solve problems faster.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] More recently, in 2024, NIST updated their post-quantum encryption standards, which includes new encryption algorithms to enhance defenses against attacks using quantum computing.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms can be expressed in many kinds of notation, including natural languages, pseudocode, flowcharts, drakon-charts, programming languages or control tables.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Natural language expressions of algorithms tend to be verbose and ambiguous and are rarely used for complex or technical algorithms.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Pseudocode, flowcharts, drakon-charts, and control tables are structured expressions of algorithms that avoid common ambiguities of natural language.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Programming languages are primarily for expressing algorithms in a computer-executable form but are also used to define or document algorithms.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithm representations can also be classified into three accepted levels of Turing machine description: high-level description, implementation description, and formal description.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] A high-level description describes the qualities of the algorithm itself, ignoring how it is implemented on the Turing machine.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] An implementation description describes the general manner in which the machine moves its head and stores data to carry out the algorithm, but does not give exact states.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In the most detail, a formal description gives the exact state table and list of transitions of the Turing machine.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] A flowchart is a graphical aid that describes and documents an algorithm.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] It has four primary symbols: arrows showing program flow, rectangles (SEQUENCE, GOTO), diamonds representing decisions, and dots (OR-tie).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Sub-structures can "nest" in rectangles, but only if a single exit occurs from the superstructure.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] It is often important to know the time, storage, or other cost an algorithm may require.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Methods have been developed to analyse algorithms to estimate these needs.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] For example, an algorithm that adds up the elements of a list of *n* numbers would have a time requirement of ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠, using big O notation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The algorithm only needs to remember two values: the sum of all the elements so far, and its current position in the input list.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] If the space required to store the input numbers is not counted, it has a space requirement of ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠, otherwise ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ is required.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Different algorithms may complete the same task with a different set of instructions in less or more time, space, or 'effort' than others.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] For example, a binary search algorithm (with cost ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠) outperforms a sequential search (cost ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ ) when used for table lookups on sorted lists.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The analysis, and study of algorithms is a discipline of computer science.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms are often studied abstractly, without referencing a specific programming language or implementation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Like other mathematical disciplines, it focuses on the algorithm's properties, not implementation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Pseudocode is typical for analysis as it is a simple and general representation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Most algorithms are implemented on particular hardware/software platforms and their algorithmic efficiency is tested using real code.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The efficiency of a particular algorithm may be insignificant for many "one-off" problems but it can be critical for algorithms designed for fast, interactive, commercial, or long-life scientific usage.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Increasing the input size often exposes inefficient algorithms that are otherwise benign.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Empirical testing is useful for uncovering unexpected interactions that affect performance.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Benchmarks may be used to compare before/after potential improvements to an algorithm after program optimization.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Empirical tests cannot fully replace formal analysis, and are difficult to perform fairly.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] To illustrate the potential improvements possible even in well-established algorithms, a recent significant innovation, relating to FFT algorithms used for image processing, can decrease processing time up to 1,000 times for medical imaging.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In general, speed improvements depend on special properties of the problem, which are very common in practical applications.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The best case of an algorithm refers to the scenario or input for which the algorithm or data structure takes the least time and resources to complete its tasks.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The worst case of an algorithm is the case that causes the algorithm or data structure to consume the maximum period of time and computational resources.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithm design may take advantage of many different approaches, such as divide-and-conquer or dynamic programming.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Techniques for designing and implementing algorithms are also called algorithm design patterns.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Examples include the template method pattern and the decorator pattern.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] An important aspect of algorithm design is efficient use of resources such as memory or time; the big O notation is used to describe how resource use changes as the size of inputs increase.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Any algorithm can be computed by any Turing complete model.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Turing completeness only requires four instruction types—conditional GOTO, unconditional GOTO, assignment, HALT.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Tausworthe augments the three Böhm-Jacopini canonical structures: SEQUENCE, IF-THEN-ELSE, and WHILE-DO, with two more: DO-WHILE and CASE.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] An additional benefit of a structured program is that it lends itself to proofs of correctness using mathematical induction.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] By themselves, algorithms are not usually patentable.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In the United States, a claim consisting solely of simple manipulations of abstract concepts, numbers, or signals does not constitute "processes", so algorithms are not patentable (as in *Gottschalk v.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] However, practical applications of algorithms can be patentable.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Diehr*, the application of a simple feedback algorithm to aid in the curing of synthetic rubber was deemed patentable.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The patenting of software is controversial, and there are criticized patents involving algorithms, especially data compression algorithms, such as Unisys's LZW patent.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Additionally, some cryptographic algorithms have export restrictions (see export of cryptography).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Problems may be suited for one implementation or the other.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] is a puzzle commonly solved using recursive implementation.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Every recursive version has an equivalent (but possibly more or less complex) iterative version, and vice versa.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Algorithms are usually discussed with the assumption that computers execute one instruction of an algorithm at a time on serial computers.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Parallel algorithms take advantage of computer architectures where multiple processors can work on a problem at the same time.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Distributed algorithms use multiple machines connected via a computer network.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Parallel and distributed algorithms divide the problem into sub-problems and collect the results back together.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Resource consumption in these algorithms is not only processor cycles on each processor but also the communication overhead between the processors.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Some sorting algorithms can be parallelized efficiently, but their communication overhead is expensive.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Iterative algorithms are generally parallelizable, but some problems have no parallel algorithms and are called inherently serial problems.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] seek an approximation that is close to the true solution.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Such algorithms have practical value for many hard problems.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] , where there is a set of items, and the goal is to pack the knapsack to get the maximum total value.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Each item has some weight and some value.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The total weight that can be carried is no more than some fixed number X.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] So, the solution must consider the weights of items as well as their value.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Another way of classifying algorithms is by their design methodology or paradigm.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Brute force is a problem-solving method of systematically trying every possible option until the optimal solution is found.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] This approach can be very time-consuming, testing every possible combination of variables.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] It is often used when other methods are unavailable or too complex.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Brute force can solve a variety of problems, including finding the shortest path between two points and cracking passwords.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] ) until the instances are small enough to solve easily.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] is an example of divide and conquer, where an unordered list is repeatedly split into smaller lists, which are sorted in the same way and then merged.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] , which solves one smaller instance of itself, and does not require a merge step.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] specifies rules for moving around a graph and is useful for such problems.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Such algorithms make some choices randomly (or pseudo-randomly).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] They find approximate solutions when finding exact solutions may be impractical (see heuristic method below).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms always return the correct answer, but their running time is only probabilistically bound, e.g.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] is not dominated by the resulting reduced algorithms.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] finds the median of an unsorted list by first sorting the list (the expensive portion), and then pulling out the middle element in the sorted list (the cheap portion).
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In this approach, multiple solutions are built incrementally and abandoned when it is determined that they cannot lead to a valid full solution.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] When searching for optimal solutions to a linear function bound by linear equality and inequality constraints, the constraints can be used directly to produce optimal solutions.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] A linear programming algorithm can solve such a problem if it can be proved that all restrictions for integer values are superficial, i.e., the solutions satisfy these restrictions anyway.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In the general case, a specialized algorithm or an algorithm that finds approximate solutions is used, depending on the difficulty of the problem.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] can be found using the shortest path to the goal from all adjacent vertices.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Unlike divide and conquer, dynamic programming subproblems often overlap.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The difference between dynamic programming and simple recursion is the caching or memoization of recursive calls.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] When subproblems are independent and do not repeat, memoization does not help; hence dynamic programming is not applicable to all complex problems.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Using memoization dynamic programming reduces the complexity of many problems from exponential to polynomial.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] , similarly to a dynamic programming, work by examining substructures, in this case not of the problem but of a given solution.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Such algorithms start with some solution and improve it by making small modifications.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] The most popular use of greedy algorithms is finding minimal spanning trees of graphs without negative cycles.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] are greedy algorithms that can solve this optimization problem.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] find solutions close to the optimal solution when finding the optimal solution is impractical.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] These algorithms get closer and closer to the optimal solution as they progress.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In principle, if run for an infinite amount of time, they will find the optimal solution.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] They can ideally find a solution very close to the optimal solution in a relatively short time.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Some, like simulated annealing, are non-deterministic algorithms while others, like tabu search, are deterministic.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] One of the simplest algorithms finds the largest number in a list of numbers of random order.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Finding the solution requires looking at every number in the list.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Assume the first number in the set is the largest.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] For each remaining number in the set: if this number is greater than the current largest, it becomes the new largest.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] When there are no unchecked numbers left in the set, consider the current largest number to be the largest in the set.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] Artificial intelligence systems have been used to discover and optimize algorithms.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, a reinforcement learning system based on AlphaZero that discovered improved sorting and hashing algorithms.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In a paper published in *Nature*, AlphaDev was reported to have discovered small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and were integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an evolutionary coding agent powered by large language models for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:digital-data/algorithm] AlphaEvolve uses language models to propose code changes, automated evaluators to test candidate solutions, and an evolutionary process to improve promising algorithms over multiple iterations.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] In formal language theory, an **alphabet**, often called a **vocabulary** in the context of terminal and nonterminal symbols, is a non-empty set of indivisible symbols/characters/glyphs, typically thought of as representing letters, characters, digits, phonemes, or even words.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] The definition is used in a diverse range of fields including logic, mathematics, computer science, and linguistics.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] An alphabet may have any cardinality ("size") and, depending on its purpose, may be finite (e.g., the alphabet of letters "a" through "z"), countable (e.g., $\{v_{1},v_{2},\ldots \}$ ), or even uncountable (e.g., $\{v_{x}:x\in \mathbb {R} \}$ ).
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] Strings, also known as "words" or "sentences", over an alphabet are defined as a sequence of the symbols from the alphabet set.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] For example, the alphabet of lowercase letters "a" through "z" can be used to form English words like "iceberg" while the alphabet of both upper and lower case letters can also be used to form proper names like "Wikipedia".
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] A common alphabet is {0,1}, the **binary alphabet**, and "00101111" is an example of a binary string.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] Infinite sequences of symbols may be considered as well (see Omega language).
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] Strings are often written as the concatenation of their symbols, and when using this notational convention it is convenient for practical purposes to restrict the symbols in an alphabet so that this notation is unambiguous.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] For instance, if the two-member alphabet is {00,0}, a string written in concatenated form as "000" is ambiguous because it is unclear if it is a sequence of three "0" symbols, a "00" followed by a "0", or a "0" followed by a "00".
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] However, this is a limitation on the notation for writing strings, not on their underlying definitions.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] Like any finite set, {00,0} can be used as an alphabet, whose strings can be written unambiguously in a different notational convention with commas separating their elements: 0,00 ≠ 0,0,0 ≠ 00,0.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] By definition, the *alphabet* of a formal language L over $\Sigma$ is the set $\Sigma$ , which can be **any** non-empty set of symbols from which every string in L is built.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] For example, the set $\Sigma =\{\_,\mathrm {a} ,\dots ,\mathrm {z} ,\mathrm {A} ,\dots ,\mathrm {Z} ,0,\mathrm {1} ,\dots ,\mathrm {9} \}$ can be the alphabet of the formal language L that means "all variable identifiers in the C programming language".
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] It is not required to use every symbol in the alphabet of L for its strings.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] Given an alphabet $\Sigma$ , the set of all strings of length n over the alphabet $\Sigma$ is indicated by $\Sigma ^{n}$ .
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] The set ${\textstyle \bigcup _{i\in \mathbb {N} }\Sigma ^{i}}$ of all finite strings (regardless of their length) is indicated by the Kleene star operator as $\Sigma ^{*}$ , and is also called the Kleene closure of $\Sigma$ .
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] The notation $\Sigma ^{\omega }$ indicates the set of all infinite sequences over the alphabet $\Sigma$ , and $\Sigma ^{\infty }$ indicates the set $\Sigma ^{\ast }\cup \Sigma ^{\omega }$ of all finite or infinite sequences.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] For example, using the binary alphabet {0,1}, the strings ε, 0, 1, 00, 01, 10, 11, 000, etc. are all in the Kleene closure of the alphabet (where ε represents the empty string).
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] Alphabets are important in the use of formal languages, automata and semiautomata.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] In most cases, for defining instances of automata, such as deterministic finite automata (DFAs), it is required to specify an alphabet from which the input strings for the automaton are built.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] In these applications, an alphabet is usually required to be a finite set, but is not otherwise restricted.
[src:digital-data/alphabet-formal-languages] When using automata, regular expressions, or formal grammars as part of string-processing algorithms, the alphabet may be assumed to be the character set of the text to be processed by these algorithms, or a subset of allowable characters from the character set.
[src:digital-data/arm-cortex-a8] The **ARM Cortex-A8** is a 32-bit processor core licensed by ARM Holdings implementing the ARMv7-A architecture.
[src:digital-data/arm-cortex-a8] Compared to the ARM11, the Cortex-A8 is a dual-issue superscalar design, and is capable of at most twice the instructions per cycle.
[src:digital-data/arm-cortex-a8] The Cortex-A8 was the first Cortex design to be adopted on a large scale in consumer devices.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:digital-data/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:digital-data/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:digital-data/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:digital-data/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:digital-data/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:digital-data/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:digital-data/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:digital-data/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:digital-data/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:digital-data/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:digital-data/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:digital-data/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:digital-data/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:digital-data/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:digital-data/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:digital-data/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:digital-data/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:digital-data/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:digital-data/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:digital-data/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:digital-data/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:digital-data/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:digital-data/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:digital-data/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:digital-data/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:digital-data/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:digital-data/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:digital-data/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:digital-data/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:digital-data/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:digital-data/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:digital-data/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:digital-data/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:digital-data/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:digital-data/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:digital-data/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:digital-data/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:digital-data/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:digital-data/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:digital-data/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:digital-data/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:digital-data/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:digital-data/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:digital-data/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:digital-data/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:digital-data/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:digital-data/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:digital-data/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:digital-data/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:digital-data/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:digital-data/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:digital-data/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:digital-data/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:digital-data/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:digital-data/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:digital-data/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:digital-data/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:digital-data/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:digital-data/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:digital-data/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:digital-data/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:digital-data/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:digital-data/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:digital-data/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:digital-data/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:digital-data/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:digital-data/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:digital-data/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:digital-data/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:digital-data/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:digital-data/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Digital data can be contrasted with *analog data*, which is represented by a value from a continuous range of real numbers.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Analog data is transmitted by an analog signal, which not only takes on continuous values but can vary continuously with time, a continuous real-valued function of time.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] An example is the air pressure variation in a sound wave.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data requires interpretation to become information.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In modern (post-1960) computer systems, all data is digital.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The word *digital* comes from the same source as the words digit and *digitus* (the Latin word for *finger*), as fingers are often used for counting.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Mathematician George Stibitz of Bell Telephone Laboratories used the word *digital* in reference to the fast electric pulses emitted by a device designed to aim and fire anti-aircraft guns in 1942.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The term is most commonly used in computing and electronics, especially where real-world information is converted to binary numeric form as in digital audio and digital photography.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Since symbols (for example, alphanumeric characters) are not continuous, representing symbols digitally is rather simpler than conversion of continuous or analog information to digital.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Instead of sampling and quantization as in analog-to-digital conversion, such techniques as polling and encoding are used.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A symbol input device usually consists of a group of switches that are polled at regular intervals to see which switches are switched.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data will be lost if, within a single polling interval, two switches are pressed, or a switch is pressed, released, and pressed again.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This polling can be done by a specialized processor in the device to prevent burdening the main CPU.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] When a new symbol has been entered, the device typically sends an interrupt, in a specialized format, so that the CPU can read it.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] For devices with only a few switches (such as the buttons on a joystick), the status of each can be encoded as bits (usually 0 for released and 1 for pressed) in a single word.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This is useful when combinations of key presses are meaningful, and is sometimes used for passing the status of modifier keys on a keyboard (such as shift and control).
[src:digital-data/digital-data] But it does not scale to support more keys than the number of bits in a single byte or word.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Devices with many switches (such as a computer keyboard) usually arrange these switches in a scan matrix, with the individual switches on the intersections of x and y lines.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] When a switch is pressed, it connects the corresponding x and y lines together.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Polling (often called scanning in this case) is done by activating each x line in sequence and detecting which y lines then have a signal, thus which keys are pressed.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] When the keyboard processor detects that a key has changed state, it sends a signal to the CPU indicating the scan code of the key and its new state.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The symbol is then encoded or converted into a number based on the status of modifier keys and the desired character encoding.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A custom encoding can be used for a specific application with no loss of data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] However, using a standard encoding such as ASCII is problematic if a symbol such as 'ß' needs to be converted but is not in the standard.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] It is estimated that in the year 1986, less than 1% of the world's technological capacity to store information was digital and in 2007 it was already 94%.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The year 2002 is assumed to be the year when humankind was able to store more information in digital than in analog format (the "beginning of the digital age").
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Digital data come in these three states: data at rest, data in transit, and data in use.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The confidentiality, integrity, and availability have to be managed during the entire lifecycle from 'birth' to the destruction of the data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] While it is generally accepted that archive data (i.e. which never changes), regardless of its storage medium, is data at rest and active data subject to constant or frequent change is data in use. “Inactive data” could be taken to mean data which may change, but infrequently.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The imprecise nature of terms such as “constant” and “frequent” means that some stored data cannot be comprehensively defined as either data at rest or in use.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] These definitions could be taken to assume that Data at Rest is a superset of data in use; however, data in use, subject to frequent change, has distinct processing requirements from data at rest, whether completely static or subject to occasional change.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Because of its nature data at rest is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect data in motion and increasingly promoted for protecting data at rest.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The encryption of data at rest should only include strong encryption methods such as AES or RSA.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Encrypted data should remain encrypted when access controls such as usernames and password fail.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Increasing encryption on multiple levels is recommended.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Cryptography can be implemented on the database housing the data and on the physical storage where the databases are stored.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data encryption keys should be updated on a regular basis.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Encryption keys should be stored separately from the data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Encryption also enables crypto-shredding at the end of the data or hardware lifecycle.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Periodic auditing of sensitive data should be part of policy and should occur on scheduled occurrences.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Finally, only store the minimum possible amount of sensitive data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens, which have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This process does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Tokens require significantly less computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This is achieved by keeping specific data fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Lower processing and storage requirements makes tokenization an ideal method of securing data at rest in systems that manage large volumes of data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A further method of preventing unwanted access to data at rest is the use of data federation especially when data is distributed globally (e.g. in off-shore archives).
[src:digital-data/digital-data] An example of this would be a European organisation which stores its archived data off-site in the US.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Under the terms of the USA PATRIOT Act the American authorities can demand access to all data physically stored within its boundaries, even if it includes personal information on European citizens with no connections to the US.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data encryption alone cannot be used to prevent this as the authorities have the right to demand decrypted information.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A data federation policy which retains personal citizen information with no foreign connections within its country of origin (separate from information which is either not personal or is relevant to off-shore authorities) is one option to address this concern.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] However, data stored in foreign countries can be accessed using legislation in the CLOUD Act.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Some cloud software as a service (SaaS) providers refer to data in use as any data currently being processed by applications, as the CPU and memory are utilized.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Because of its nature, data in use is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data in use, or memory, can contain sensitive data including digital certificates, encryption keys, intellectual property (software algorithms, design data), and personally identifiable information.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Compromising data in use enables access to encrypted data at rest and data in motion.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] For example, someone with access to random access memory can parse that memory to locate the encryption key for data at rest.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Once they have obtained that encryption key, they can decrypt encrypted data at rest.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Threats to data in use can come in the form of cold boot attacks, malicious hardware devices, rootkits and bootkits.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect Data in Motion and Data at Rest and increasingly recognized as an optimal method for protecting Data in Use.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] There have been multiple projects to encrypt memory.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Microsoft Xbox systems are designed to provide memory encryption and the company PrivateCore presently has a commercial software product vCage to provide attestation along with full memory encryption for x86 servers.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Several papers have been published highlighting the availability of security-enhanced x86 and ARM commodity processors.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In that work, an ARM Cortex-A8 processor is used as the substrate on which a full memory encryption solution is built.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Process segments (for example, stack, code or heap) can be encrypted individually or in composition.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This work marks the first full memory encryption implementation on a mobile general-purpose commodity processor.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The system provides both confidentiality and integrity protections of code and data which are encrypted everywhere outside the CPU boundary.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] For x86 systems, AMD has a Secure Memory Encryption (SME) feature introduced in 2017 with Epyc.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Intel has promised to deliver its Total Memory Encryption (TME) feature in an upcoming CPU.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Operating system kernel patches such as TRESOR and Loop-Amnesia modify the operating system so that CPU registers can be used to store encryption keys and avoid holding encryption keys in RAM.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] While this approach is not general purpose and does not protect all data in use, it does protect against cold boot attacks.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Encryption keys are held inside the CPU rather than in RAM so that data at rest encryption keys are protected against attacks that might compromise encryption keys in memory.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Enclaves enable an “enclave” to be secured with encryption in RAM so that enclave data is encrypted while in RAM but available as clear text inside the CPU and CPU cache.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Intel Corporation has introduced the concept of “enclaves” as part of its Software Guard Extensions.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Intel revealed an architecture combining software and CPU hardware in technical papers published in 2013.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Several cryptographic tools, including secure multi-party computation and homomorphic encryption, allow for the private computation of data on untrusted systems.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data in use could be operated upon while encrypted and never exposed to the system doing the processing.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data in transit can be separated into two categories: information that flows over the public or untrusted network such as the Internet and data that flows in the confines of a private network such as a corporate or enterprise local area network (LAN).
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data within a computer, in most cases, moves as parallel data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data moving to or from a computer, in most cases, moves as serial data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data sourced from an analog device, such as a temperature sensor, may be converted to digital using an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data representing quantities, characters, or symbols on which operations are performed by a computer are stored and recorded on magnetic, optical, electronic, or mechanical recording media, and transmitted in the form of digital electrical or optical signals.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data pass in and out of computers via peripheral devices.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Physical computer memory elements consist of an address and a byte/word of data storage.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Digital data are often stored in relational databases, like tables or SQL databases, and can generally be represented as abstract key/value pairs.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data can be organized in many different types of data structures, including arrays, graphs, and objects.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data structures can store data of many different types, including numbers, strings and even other data structures.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Metadata helps translate data to information.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Metadata may be implied, specified or given.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data relating to physical events or processes will have a temporal component.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This is the case when a device such as a temperature logger receives data from a temperature sensor.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] When the temperature is received it is assumed that the data has a temporal reference of *now*.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] So the device records the date, time and temperature together.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] When the data logger communicates temperatures, it must also report the date and time as metadata for each temperature reading.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Fundamentally, computers follow a sequence of instructions they are given in the form of data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A set of instructions to perform a given task (or tasks) is called a *program*.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A program is data in the form of coded instructions to control the operation of a computer or other machine.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In the nominal case, the program, as executed by the computer, will consist of machine code.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The elements of storage manipulated by the program, but not actually executed by the central processing unit (CPU), are also data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] At its most essential, a single datum is a value stored at a specific location.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Therefore, it is possible for computer programs to operate on other computer programs, by manipulating their programmatic data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] To store data bytes in a file, they have to be serialized in a file format.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Typically, programs are stored in special file types, different from those used for other data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Executable files contain programs; all other files are also data files.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] However, executable files may also contain data used by the program which is built into the program.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In particular, some executable files have a data segment, which nominally contains constants and initial values for variables, both of which can be considered data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The line between program and data can become blurry.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] An interpreter, for example, is a program.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The input data to an interpreter is itself a program, just not one expressed in native machine language.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In many cases, the interpreted program will be a human-readable text file, which is manipulated with a text editor program.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Metaprogramming similarly involves programs manipulating other programs as data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Programs like compilers, linkers, debuggers, program updaters, virus scanners and such use other programs as their data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] For example, a user might first instruct the operating system to load a word processor program from one file, and then use the running program to open and edit a document stored in another file.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In this example, the document would be considered data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] If the word processor also features a spell checker, then the dictionary (word list) for the spell checker would also be considered data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The algorithms used by the spell checker to suggest corrections would be either machine code data or text in some interpretable programming language.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In an alternate usage, binary files (which are not human-readable) are sometimes called *data* as distinguished from human-readable *text*.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The total amount of digital data in 2007 was estimated to be 281 billion gigabytes (281 exabytes).
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Keys in data provide the context for values.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Regardless of the structure of data, there is always a key component present.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Keys in data and data-structures are essential for giving meaning to data values.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Without a key that is directly or indirectly associated with a value, or collection of values in a structure, the values become meaningless and cease to be data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] That is to say, there has to be a key component linked to a value component in order for it to be considered data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Random access memory (RAM) holds data that the CPU has direct access to.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] A CPU may only manipulate data within its processor registers or memory.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This is as opposed to data storage, where the CPU must direct the transfer of data between the storage device (disk, tape...) and memory.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] RAM is an array of linear contiguous locations that a processor may read or write by providing an address for the read or write operation.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The processor may operate on any location in memory at any time in any order.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In RAM the smallest element of data is the binary bit.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The capabilities and limitations of accessing RAM are processor specific.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In general main memory is arranged as an array of locations beginning at address 0 (hexadecimal 0).
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Each location can store usually 8 or 32 bits depending on the computer architecture.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data keys need not be a direct hardware address in memory.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Indirect, abstract and logical keys codes can be stored in association with values to form a data structure.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data structures have predetermined offsets (or links or paths) from the start of the structure, in which data values are stored.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Therefore, the data key consists of the key to the structure plus the offset (or links or paths) into the structure.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In such an organization of data, the data key is usually a value in one (or a composite of the values in several) of the columns.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The tabular view of repeating data structures is only one of many possibilities.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Repeating data structures can be organised hierarchically, such that nodes are linked to each other in a cascade of parent-child relationships.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Values and potentially more complex data-structures are linked to the nodes.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Thus the nodal hierarchy provides the key for addressing the data structures associated with the nodes.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This representation can be thought of as an inverted tree.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Modern computer operating system file systems are a common example; and XML is another.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Data has some inherent features when it is sorted on a key.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] All the values for subsets of the key appear together.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] When passing sequentially through groups of the data with the same key, or a subset of the key changes, this is referred to in data processing circles as a break, or a control break.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] It particularly facilitates the aggregation of data values on subsets of a key.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Until the advent of bulk non-volatile memory like flash, persistent data storage was traditionally achieved by writing the data to external block devices like magnetic tape and disk drives.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] These devices typically seek to a location on the magnetic media and then read or write blocks of data of a predetermined size.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In this case, the seek location on the media, is the data key and the blocks are the data values.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Early used *raw disk* data file-systems or disc operating systems reserved contiguous blocks on the disc drive for data files.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In those systems, the files could be filled up, running out of data space before all the data had been written to them.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Thus much unused data space was reserved unproductively to ensure adequate free space for each file.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Later file-systems introduced partitions.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] They reserved blocks of disc data space for partitions and used the allocated blocks more economically, by dynamically assigning blocks of a partition to a file as needed.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] To achieve this, the file system had to keep track of which blocks were used or unused by data files in a catalog or file allocation table.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Though this made better use of the disc data space, it resulted in fragmentation of files across the disc, and a concomitant performance overhead due additional seek time to read the data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Modern file systems reorganize fragmented files dynamically to optimize file access times.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Further developments in file systems resulted in virtualization of disc drives i.e. where a logical drive can be defined as partitions from a number of physical drives.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Retrieving a small subset of data from a much larger set may imply inefficiently searching through the data sequentially.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] **Indexes** are a way to copy out keys and location addresses from data structures in files, tables and data sets, then organize them using inverted tree structures to reduce the time taken to retrieve a subset of the original data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In order to do this, the key of the subset of data to be retrieved must be known before retrieval begins.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The most popular indexes are the B-tree and the dynamic hash key indexing methods.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Indexing is overhead for filing and retrieving data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] There are other ways of organizing indexes, e.g. sorting the keys and using a binary search algorithm.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] 2. at run time, the creation of references to in-memory data-structures of objects that have been instantiated from a class library.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] It is only after instantiation that an object of a specified class exists.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] After an object's reference is cleared, the object also ceases to exist.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The memory locations where the object's data was stored are garbage and are reclassified as unused memory available for reuse.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] The advent of databases introduced a further layer of abstraction for persistent data storage.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Databases use metadata, and a structured query language protocol between client and server systems, communicating over a computer network, using a two phase commit logging system to ensure transactional completeness, when saving data.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Modern scalable and high-performance data persistence technologies, such as Apache Hadoop, rely on massively parallel distributed data processing across many commodity computers on a high bandwidth network.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] In such systems, the data is distributed across multiple computers and therefore any particular computer in the system must be represented in the key of the data, either directly, or indirectly.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] This enables the differentiation between two identical sets of data, each being processed on a different computer at the same time.
[src:digital-data/digital-data] Even though digital signals are generally associated with the binary electronic digital systems used in modern electronics and computing, digital systems are actually ancient, and need not be binary or electronic.
